The course is aimed at introducing a new paradigm of  sociology and developing of a new way of  looking at children as units of observation and active social agents. The course overviews childhood as a social phenomenon,  its theoretical and methodological aspects of research. The 
course is addressed to students of social sciences  and other disciplines, who in their future career will 
work with children, will do research with and about children or work in the field of social policy. 
The course participants will carry out their own research focusing on varied topics such as social problems of children, rights of the child, childhood policies, social representations of children in media; critical analysis of llaws and policy regulations from the perspective of children's rights and welfare. Students attending the course will write their own childhood memory stories. All the students' contributions will be made in a compiled form available for the whole course and as a part of teaching material. The suggested readings are made available over the SISObjectives/eesmärkid:  The course is aimed at: - introducing a new paradigm of  sociology;  - developing a new approach  of looking at children as units of observation and as active social agents; - advancing knowledge and skills of critical analysis of child-related policies and understanding the rights of the child; - developing child-centered views on research about and with children and understanding of ethical principles doing research related to children; - practicing skills of academic writing and discussion by doing mini-research and giving presentation in the seminar; - creating knowledge basis for doing child-centered and policy relevant research; - creating basis for better understanding of other courses related to children and childhood policies.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  After  passing the course the student:
- understands the theoretical framework of childhood sociology and can associate it with children's rights and childhood policies;
- can make difference between the adult-centered and child-centered way of thinking;
- knows and understands the rights of the child;
- has knowledge and skills for analysing children-related policies;
- has basic knowledge of doing research with children
- is able to forsee and solve ethical problems in research about and with children;
- can express oneself in written and oral form when discussing the topics related to children.
